      "content": "Shrinkage, an increase of 5% in the quarterly reports, means you've lost some inventory, which directly impacts your inventory turnover ratio. You need to account for this loss when calculating how quickly you're moving your stock. Think of shrinkage as a hidden drain, as the inventory is essentially being consumed without a sale.\n\nTo factor this in, you should adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) or your ending inventory figures. If shrinkage is a direct loss, you need to subtract that loss from your reported inventory levels to get a more accurate picture of the inventory that was actually available for sale.\n\nThis adjustment will make your inventory turnover ratio reflect a more realistic efficiency level for the warehouse. It shows that even if sales are steady, the actual inventory pool is smaller than you thought.",
