      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are correct; subtracting the shrinkage from the ending inventory will indeed make the denominator smaller, which will cause the inventory turnover ratio to appear higher. However, you must be careful, as you are trying to isolate the *true* efficiency, not just manipulate the numbers.\n\nTo find the root cause, you need to start looking at the logs, focusing on the high-value component aisle. Look for discrepancies in movement logs, especially for high-value items. You should be looking for patterns, such as unusual pick rates, missing cycle counts, or unauthorized access logs around those specific shelves.\n\nA good audit involves cross-referencing inventory transaction logs with security footage, shift reports, and employee access records. This helps you pinpoint the exact moment and location where the stock seems to vanish.",
